<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>UoG-ENG4118 Robotics 4 on ZCHENG LI</title><link>https://zcheng-li.github.io/en/docs/my-blog/robotics/</link><description>Recent content in UoG-ENG4118 Robotics 4 on ZCHENG LI</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><atom:link href="https://zcheng-li.github.io/en/docs/my-blog/robotics/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>L3.Knimatics</title><link>https://zcheng-li.github.io/en/docs/my-blog/robotics/robo_l3/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://zcheng-li.github.io/en/docs/my-blog/robotics/robo_l3/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="l3kinematics">
 L3.Kinematics
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#l3kinematics">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>Kinematcis describe the &lt;strong>position&lt;/strong> and &lt;strong>orientation&lt;/strong> of a robot. These depends on the translational and rotational relationship of &lt;strong>all the joints&lt;/strong> for a robot. These are called &lt;strong>transformation&lt;/strong>.&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>kinematcis = position + orientation&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>transformation = translation + rotation&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>Transformation is defined in terms of specific reference frames i.e. coordinate systems in space.&lt;/p>
